{{distinguish|Jibu language (Papua New Guinea)}} {{Infobox language |name = Jibu |states = [[Nigeria]] |region = [[Taraba State]] |speakers = 30,000 |date=1997 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4= [[Jukunoid languages|Jukunoid]] |fam5= Central |fam6= Jukun |iso3=jib |glotto=jibu1239 |glottorefname=Jibu }}
'''Jibu''' is a [[Jukunoid language]] spoken in the [[Taraba State]] of [[Nigeria]] by 30,000 people.
== Phonology == In Jibu, there are 18 consonant phonemes, 9 vowels (which are represented just using three letters), and three tones (rising, mid-level, and falling). In Jibu, nasalization, labialization, and palatalization are considered to be part of the syllable, and are written along with it after the vowel. [[Nasalization]] is represented with ''n'', except when it is at the end of a syllable it becomes doubled (/kʲã/ becomes ''kyann''). [[Labialization]] is represented with ''w'', and [[Palatalization (phonetics)|palatalization]] with ''y'' respectively.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Jibu Narrative Discourse Structure|last=Bradley|first=Virginia|publisher=SIL|year=1971|isbn=|location=|pages=15}}</ref>
=== Vowels === In Jibu, there are 9 phonemically different [[Vowel|vowels]], which are represented by three different symbols. A tenth sound resembling /u/ (as in ''y<u>ou</u>''), is only used in loanwords from other languages, such as the neighboring [[Hausa language|Hausa]], and is represented by ''u''. {| class="wikitable" |+Table of vowels in Jibu ! ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Central vowel|Central]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Close vowel|Close]] |i {{IPAslink|i}} |i {{IPAslink|ɨ}} |u {{IPAslink|u}} |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Mid vowel|Open Mid]] |a {{IPAslink|ɛ}} | | |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Mid vowel|Close Mid]] |a {{IPAslink|e}} | |o {{IPAslink|o}} |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Open-mid vowel|Open Mid]] | | |a {{IPAslink|ɔ}} |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Near-open vowel|Near Open]] |a {{IPAslink|æ}} | | |- style="text-align:center;" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | |a {{IPAslink|a}} | |}
=== Consonants === Jibu has 18 different [[consonant]] phonemes. Some different phonemes are represented by the same symbol, such as /ʃ/ and /s/ being both represented as ''s'' in their older modified [[Americanist phonetic notation|Americanist Phonetic Notation]] [[Orthography|orthographic]] forms. If all of the consonant phonemes are represented using their older [[Americanist phonetic notation|Americanist Phonetic Notation]] counterparts, there is no orthographic overlap. The sound /ɗ/, which is used in some [[Hausa language|Hausa]] loanwords, is commonly represented using ''<nowiki/>'d''. {| class="wikitable" style="margin:autmargin:auto;" |+Table of consonant phonemes in Jibu ! colspan="2" rowspan="2" | ! rowspan="2" |[[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! colspan="2" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- !<small>[[sibilant]]</small> !<small>[[Palato-alveolar consonant|palato-]]</small> <small>[[Palato-alveolar consonant|alveolar]]</small> |- style="text-align:center;" ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m {{IPAslink|m}} | colspan="2" |n, l {{IPAslink|n}} | |ng {{IPAslink|ŋ}} |- style="text-align:center;" ! rowspan="2" |[[Plosive]] !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> |b {{IPAslink|b}} | colspan="2" |d {{IPAslink|d}} | |g, ꞡ {{IPAslink|g}} |- style="text-align:center;" !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|unvoiced]]</small> |p {{IPAslink|p}} | colspan="2" |t {{IPAslink|t}} | |k {{IPAslink|k}} |- style="text-align:center;" ! rowspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> | |v {{IPAslink|v}} | | | |- style="text-align:center;" !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|unvoiced]]</small> | |f {{IPAslink|f}} | | | |- style="text-align:center;" ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | |y {{IPAslink|j}} |w {{IPAslink|w}} |- style="text-align:center;" ! colspan="2" |[[Flap consonant|Flap]] | | colspan="2" |r, ř {{IPAslink|ɾ}} | | |- style="text-align:center;" ! rowspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Alveolar]] !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small> | |z, đ {{IPAslink|z}} |j, z {{IPAslink|ʒ}} | | |- style="text-align:center;" !<small>[[Voice (phonetics)|unvoiced]]</small> | |s {{IPAslink|s}} |s, š {{IPAslink|ʃ}} | | |}
=== Tones === Jibu has three tones (four if the base tone is included). These tones are high (´), lowered-mid (') and low (`). The base tone is not written on words and in more recent publications, neither is the lowered-mid tone.
{| class="wikitable" |+Comparison of Jibu tones<ref name=":1">Blench, Rodger. [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Niger-Congo/BC/Jukunoid/Jibu%20Dictionary.pdf ''Jibu Dictionary'']. p. 18</ref> ! !Jibu !English !IPA |- !Rising Tone |káb |all, finish (idiophone) |/kɛ́b/ |- !Mid-Tone |kab |to dip out, to dig, to snap off, surpass |/kɛb/ |- !Falling Tone |kàb |provisional hut |/kɛ̀b/ |}
== Orthography == The system used today in Jibu includes some symbols for transcribing sounds in Hausa loanwords, the older system, which is a slightly modified version of Americanist Phonetic Notation, does not include a symbol for the transcription of ''h'', and includes the fact that multiple phonemes are [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcribed]] as a single symbol in multiple cases. {| class="wikitable sortable" !Modern System<ref name=":1" /> !Previous System (Modified [[Americanist phonetic notation|APN]])<ref name=":0" /> !IPA |- |m |m |/m/ |- |n |n, l |/n/ |- |ng, ŋ |ng, ŋ |/ŋ/ |- |b |b |/b/ |- |d |d |/d/ |- |g |g, ꞡ |/g/ |- |p |p |/p/ |- |t |t |/t/ |- |k |k |/k/ |- |v |v |/v/ |- |f |f |/f/ |- |y |y |/j/ |- |w |w |/w/ |- |r |r, ř |/ɾ/ |- |z |z, đ |/z/ |- |j |j, z |/ʒ/ |- |s |s |/s/ |- |sh |s, š |/ʃ/ |- |''<nowiki/>'d'' |''<nowiki/>'d'' |''/ɗ/'' |- |''h'' |''-'' |''/h/'' |}
== Verbs == In Jibu, verbs are not conjugated, which is a common aspect among Junkanoid languages. Instead, the pronoun is placed before the verb, and all aspect markers are placed before the pronoun.<ref name=":1" />
Intransitive: á (work! - ''á sar'')
Continuative action: ri (are working - ''ri sar'')
Completed action: hiŋ (did work - ''hiŋ sar'')
Completive action: rìg, rìghiŋ (work has been completed - ''rìg sar'')
== Pronouns == Jibu pronouns do not reflect gender, the word ''wá'' meaning he, she, or it, unlike English, does not have multiple forms based on gender.<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" ! !1st Person !2nd Person !3rd Person |- !Singular |''mí'' (I) |''wú'' (you) |''wá'' (he, she, it) |- !Plural |''yá'' (we) |''ná'' (you pl.) |''bá'' (they) |}
== Phrases == * Good afternoon - aku àyúnn-à * Good morning - bib kyàr * Sorry! - àtau! * Hurry! - á àzwab! * Hello, thank you - ísoko, soko<ref name=":1" />
